lish mariner who served with Sir Francis Drake's Cádiz expedition of 1587. In 1592 he commanded a successful privateering expedition to the West Indies, taking 19 Spanish vessels. He married three times and had two daughters and two sons, one of whom, John, lived to acquire land in VA."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs William Newport was born about 1213, in Pembrokeshire, Wales. She had at least 1 daughter with William Newport."},"et":{"about 1213–":"umbes 1213–Surnud","1213–Male":"1213–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1213–Female":"1213–Surnud","1213":"1213","about 1213":"umbes 1213","1240":"1240","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1213–":"noin 1213–Kuollut","1213–Male":"1213–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1213–Female":"1213–Kuollut","1213":"1213","about 1213":"noin 1213","1240":"1240","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Haverfordwest, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1213–":"environ 1213–Décédée","1213–Male":"1213–Décédé","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","1213–Female":"1213–Décédée","1213":"1213","about 1213":"environ 1213","1240":"1240","Pembrok